# --- Rust ---
# Build artifacts (cargo default output dir).
/target

# Cargo.lock IS committed for this crate (issue #9, gate item #10). The usual
# "libraries don't commit lockfiles" convention optimizes for downstream
# resolution flexibility — which is preserved, because consumers ignore a
# dependency's committed lock. What we gain is REPRODUCIBLE CI: the MSRV (1.81)
# job and the byte-contract tests resolve the SAME dependency graph on every
# run, so a transitive update can't silently move the real MSRV floor or perturb
# canonical bytes between CI runs. For a crate whose whole purpose is
# deterministic, self-certifying bytes, that reproducibility is worth more than
# the convention. (So: NO `Cargo.lock` entry here.)
